bioghist.head: History
bioghist.p: the COO is responsible for overseeing construction, renovation, operation, logistics and security of the University's physical plant; human resources and payroll; purchasing; accounts payable; information technology; business services; and public and environmental safety, as well as formulation of strategy and policies to ensure effective administration, sound business practices, safety and regulatory compliance within these areas, in conformity with policies established by the board of trustees. http://www.uconn.edu/administration/vp_coo.php
Finance and Administration separated into two departments in 1988 and reunited in 1991. The responsibilities were again separated in 2000 with the appointment of Lorraine Aronson.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The records of this office pertain to the administrative operations involved in the everyday activities of the University--budget, finance, payroll, human resources, facilities, etc. The collection contains correspondence, reports, studies, minutes, financial and legal records, publications, photographs and maps. Of special interest are the legal records in Series IV and Series VIII, which provide insight into the physical growth and expansion of the University in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. A small glimpse into the lives of Depression-era students, while attending and afterwards, can be extrapolated from the correspondence with the Student Loan Committee in Series V. The records of the VP &CFO (2000-) are described in the finding aid for that office.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The records of several administrative tenures have been combined to form the following series:
Series I: Administrative Records ( undated, 1908-1986) includes correspondence, reports, studies, minutes and related materials from several tenures.
Series II: Construction Projects ( undated, 1896-1970) includes correspondence, legal and financial records pertaining to construction at the University, primarily on the Storrs campus.
Series III: Vendor Materials ( 1916-1977) contains contracts, brochures and correspondence with companies doing business with the institution.
Series IV: Property Transfers and Bequests ( undated, 1875-1972) includes copies of deeds and related legal documents pertaining to the transfer of property to or from the University.
Series V: Student Loan Committee Correspondence ( 1920-1936) includes correspondence between the committee and alumni of the institution in regard to the repayment of loans.
Series VI: Photographs ( undated) contains photographs removed from Series I-V.
Series VII: Oversize Materials ( undated, 1915-1975) contains oversize maps, blueprints and plats extracted from Series I-V, as well as loose in the collection.

Series VIII: Financial Records ( undated, 1899-1930) contains ledgers and payroll records from the early years of the institution. These records provide insight into the activities and programs at the University during years in which the administrative records are incomplete. Materials transferred from the VP&CFO Office are described in the finding aid for that office.
